Adversarial review (review-1.json):
  Opus 4.7 via Agent tool; verdict: ship; 0 blockers; 5 nits.
  Nits: historyId-omitted edge (Gmail always returns it), 404-from-
  unrelated-endpoint heuristic, 1h LIST_THREADS window vs longer
  outages, from-filter substring (`alice@example.com` matches
  `malice@example.com`), label_ids array drops all but first.
  None require changes for F.4 to ship; payload contract + spec
  verify clauses fully met.

Notes / decisions:
  - Reused F.3's direct-fetch pattern instead of importing
    ComposioClient from shared/ — keeps Lambda bundle small and
    avoids accidentally writing to external_action_audit (which is
    for tool-call observability, not adapter polling reads).
  - Dedup via Set on message.id is necessary because Gmail's history
    API can return the same message in multiple `messagesAdded`
    entries within a single response (e.g. labelAdded + messageAdded
    on the same row, though we restrict history_types to
    messageAdded only).
  - HistoryTooOldError uses both instanceof and a tagged property
    (`_historyTooOld: true`) — the property check is the bundle-safe
    fallback in case esbuild rewrites the class.
  - LIST_THREADS fallback's 1h window is a deliberate anti-spam
    tradeoff vs. replaying everything Gmail still has (~7d). The
    history-too-old path should be rare (only when polling has been
    broken for >7d), and replaying a week of mail as cloud_runs
    would be operator-hostile.
  - Adapter does NOT count per-message FETCH failures against the
    poll-level circuit breaker — they fall through to "emit with
    sparse payload" so a single bad message doesn't pause polling.

